To simplify and evaluate the given expression $[\left(x-y\right)^{2}-x\left(3x-2y\right)+\left(x+y\right)\left(x-y\right)]\div 2x$ with $x=1$ and $y=-2$, we follow these steps:

1. Expand and simplify the expression inside the brackets:
\begin{align*}
&= [x^{2}-2xy+y^{2}-3x^{2}+2xy+x^{2}-y^{2}]\div 2x \\
&= [x^{2}-2xy+y^{2}-3x^{2}+2xy+x^{2}-y^{2}]\div 2x \\
&= (-x^{2})\div 2x
\end{align*}

2. Simplify the expression further:
\begin{align*}
&= -\frac{x^{2}}{2x} \\
&= -\frac{1}{2}x
\end{align*}

3. Substitute $x=1$ and $y=-2$ into the simplified expression:
\begin{align*}
&= -\frac{1}{2}(1) \\
&= -\frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the original expression evaluates to $\boxed{-\frac{1}{2}}$ when $x=1$ and $y=-2$.
